To find the symmetric difference of (A Δ B) Δ C, we first need to find the symmetric difference of A and B, and then find the symmetric difference of the result with C.

The symmetric difference of two sets, A and B, is the set of elements which are in either A or B, but not in both. Mathematically, it can be represented as (A ∪ B) - (A ∩ B).

1. Find A Δ B:
A = {1, 2, 3}
B = {2, 3, 4}

A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4}
A ∩ B = {2, 3}
(A Δ B) = (A ∪ B) - (A ∩ B) = {1, 4}

Now we have (A Δ B) = {1, 4}.

2. Find (A Δ B) Δ C:
(A Δ B) = {1, 4}
C = {3, 4, 5}

(A Δ B) ∪ C = {1, 3, 4, 5}
(A Δ B) ∩ C = {4}
((A Δ B) Δ C) = ((A Δ B) ∪ C) - ((A Δ B) ∩ C) = {1, 3, 5}

So, the symmetric difference of (A Δ B) Δ C is {1, 3, 5}.
